opment programs, this case study, set in post-Soviet Tajikistan’s remote eastern province of Badakhshan, draws on extensive ethnographic and historical material to examine a "revolving drug fund" program—used by numerous nongovernmental organizations globally to address shortages of high-quality pharmaceuticals in poor communities. Provocative, rigorous, and accessible, Blind Spot offers a cautionary tale about the forces driving decision making in health and development policy today, illustrating how the privatization of health care can have catastrophic outcomes for some of the world’s most vulnerable populations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHealth services accessibilityvCongresses. 0aMedical carezTajikistan. 0aMedical policyxTajikistanxKūḣistonī Badakhshon. 0aMedical policyzTajikistanzKūḣistonī Badakhshon. 0aMedical policy. 0aNon-governmental organizations. 0aPublic health administrationxTajikistanxKūḣistonī Badakhshon. 0aPublic health administrationzTajikistanzKūḣistonī Badakhshon. 0aPublic healthxTajikistanxKūḣistonī Badakhshon. 0aPublic healthzTajikistanzKūḣistonī Badakhshon. 0aPublic healthzTajikistan. 0aWorld health. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095873940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958739/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles